column20: Vermont Department of Fish and Wildlife (Vermont Warden Service)
column21: Wild game meat donation program,Natural resource state agency
column22: The Venison for Vermonters program is run by game wardens within the Vermont Department of Fish and Wildlife. It is a program that focuses primarily on salvaging roadkill deer, moose and bear which are then processed and given to Food Shelves, individuals, and outreach programs across the state. The program also accepts hunter donations of whole large game.
column65: We no longer keep track of species specific donation information because it was proving to be too labor intensive. However, on average I would estimate that 70% of the meat donated is white-tailed deer, approximately 25% moose, and approximately 5% bear. Again, these are simply estimates since we no longer track species information for donations.  Depending on the year and which wardens are participating in the program, moose can make up a larger or smaller percentage of donations. For instance, in 2020-2021, the program produced over 3,000lbs of meat, and about two thirds of that was moose meat. Much of the moose meat has come from the Northeastern part of Vermont where moose are more abundant. In recent years, we have had less moose meat because the butcher who used to process meat in northeastern Vermont retired from the business and we are no longer able to use him as a processor in that region. That said, our program only process meat from moose, deer, and bear, and we rely mostly on white tailed deer.
column80: Most of our meat comes from salvageable roadkills, so hunter participation was not an issue. Vermont does not require USDA inspection for wild game. The Vermont Food Bank will not accept donations of non-inspected meat. However, there are countless food shelves throughout the state who do not have those restrictions and who are grateful for our wild game donations.
column84: Food shelves through the state are always eager to receive meat donations. If we had more meat to give, they would gladly take it. Quality protein is always hard to come by for local food shelves.
column91: The last category "other" refers to warden participation since our program relies almost exclusively on roadkill donated by Vermont state game wardens. Most of the meat processing is also conducted by VT game wardens.
column98: We do not yet list that info on our website. Our program is still small and we do not have an established network of processors or adequate funding to pay processors.
column109: The program is run entirely by Vermont game wardens (mainly one warden). In the past we have also had a wild game processor who is paid by the job. However, that processor closed up shop, and our Dpt has not had the funds to pay another processor. For this reason, nearly all meat currently being processed for the program is being processed by a single game warden. This warden (in addition to her other duties as a game warden) collects wild game from salvageable roadkills, processes the game, and distributes to food shelves. Her work hours relating to this program is unknown.
column124: There is currently no real funding source for the Venison for Vermonters program. On duty game wardens are solely responsible for the program and its survival in addition to their other duties.

column31:
In 1992, hunters in Missouri began a program to share the deer they harvested with those less fortunate. From that beginning developed a statewide system run by the Conservation Department (MDC) and the Conservation Federation of Missouri called Share The Harvest, a program that provides an easy way for hunters to donate venison to Missourians in need of red meat.

Share The Harvest is a WIN WIN WIN program. Hunters win by doing their part to help people in need, cooperating processing plants win by getting positive feedback for their involvement and donations of locker space, and participating organizations win by having a ready-made service project for a good cause. Plus, the Department of Conservation has yet another tool to use in the management of Missouri’s valuable deer resource.
